CDC
June 18 at 3:25 PM ·

Protect yourself and help reduce the spread of COVID-19 when around people that you do not live with at events and gatherings:

- Stay home when you are sick
- Try to stay at least 6 feet apart from other people when possible
- Wear a cloth face covering if able, especially when social distancing is difficult
- Wash your hands with soap and water for 20 seconds or use hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol if soap and water are not readily available
- Avoid congregated areas like food lines and restrooms
- Avoid sharing items with others

To learn more, check out: https://bit.ly/3fwgjQl

CDC
March 15 at 9:05 PM ·

New CDC recommendation: Starting immediately and for the next 8 weeks, CDC recommends cancelling all events of 50 or more people.

Ongoing guidance recommends that, in areas where there is even minimal COVID-19, events likely to include 10 or more people at high-risk for serious issues should be cancelled. People at higher risk include older adults and people who have chronic medical conditions such as lung and heart disease, as well as diabetes.

If there is substantial spread in your area, all gatherings should be cancelled.
https://bit.ly/2xyUfDQ

Toomey, M.D., M.P.H., Georgia Department of Public Health (DPH) commissioner, announced a daily status report page for confirmed COVID-19 cases in Georgia. This will replace nightly news releases from the Governor’s Office and DPH. The report updates every night at midnight to ensure accurate and regular information is provided to the public. For accurate and reliable information about COVID-19 log on to https://dph.georgia.gov/novelcoronavirus or https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html.

post_text:
Cicely Thomas, M.Ed., RDN, LD, WIC nutrition service director for the Georgia Department of Public Health Northwest Health District in Rome, received from Georgia Governor Brian Kemp today at the state capitol a proclamation he issued recognizing today as Registered Dietitian/Nutritionist Day, or RDN Day, a day set aside to honor experts in the field of nutrition.

Of the 17 Nutritionists on our Northwest Health District WIC team at both the county and district level, seven are RDNs, credentialed individuals who meet the required level of competency in the science of nutrition. Today especially we recognize their dedication to the study of nutrition science and the many public health services they provide to the people and communities of Northwest Georgia.

We also salute Cicely for arranging the governor’s proclamation honoring all RDNs in Georgia, not just those in the Northwest Health District. Photo: (l-r), Cicely Thomas, Governor Kemp

COVID-19: What Older Adults Need To Know

CDC
March 10 at 4:25 PM ·

If you are an older adult or have a severe chronic medical condition, prepare in advance for the possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in your community. Take extra measures to put distance between yourself and other people to reduce your risk of being exposed:

• Stay home as much as possible
• Have enough household items and groceries on hand if you need to stay home
• Monitor your health and keep in touch with your doctor

Learn how to be prepared if COVID-19 starts spreading in your community: http://bit.ly/2TDQVQm

Georgia Department of Education
March 3 at 5:02 PM ·

We are working closely with the Office of the Governor, the Georgia Department of Public Health and other agencies to ensure local school districts, parents, and students have the most accurate and up-to-date information regarding COVID-19 (commonly called coronavirus).

Regarding school closures: we are following the direction of the Georgia Department of Public Health, and advising local school districts to follow the direction of their local board of health. At this time, DPH has advised us that students who are not ill can safely attend schools. We are in regular contact with DPH and will immediately inform school districts if their recommendation changes.

For more information and answers to frequently asked questions, click here: https://www.gadoe.org/External-Affairs-and-Policy/communications/Pages/coronavirus.aspx

While information so far suggests that most COVID-19 illness is mild, a report out of China suggests serious illness occurs in 16% of cases. Older people and people with underlying health conditions like heart disease, lung disease and diabetes, for example, were about twice as likely to develop serious complications compared to otherwise younger, healthier people who were ill with novel coronavirus.

To protect yourself from #COVID19, the same measures that are urged to prevent the spread of any respiratory virus are increasingly important for all Georgians:

- Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer.
- Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth with unwashed hands.
- Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
- Stay home when you are sick.
https://dph.georgia.gov

post_text:
A septic tank should be checked every 3 to 7 years to see if it needs to be pumped out. If your system is over 5 years old, it may be due for pumping. Lack of maintenance can result in repairs costing thousands of dollars and put your community water supply at risk.

Environmental Health (EH) staff at your local county health department encourage you to properly maintain your septic tank and can answer any questions you have. This brochure provides useful information on pumping your septic tank and has contact information for your local county health department’s EH office. Download it here: https://nwgapublichealth.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Pumping-your-Tank-brochure.pdf

It's been just over a week since Georgia Department of Public Health Northwest Health District employees from the district office and all ten county health departments gathered for an awesome day of organizational fellowship, fun, and health-oriented learning. It couldn't have happened without some special folks.

Thanks to our district office Wellness Committee for all the hard work planning and executing this special event. In the photo in this post, they are l-r (standing)Tiffany Addison, Rewa Pressley, April Butler, Kassi Pichardo, Amanda Hunter, and (kneeling) Sobia Sattar.

Thanks again, also, to our keynote speakers Jennifer Burkholder, GA DPH deputy chief nurse of emerging health threats, who spoke about “Finding Meaning in Adversity” and Maura Kalafut, an associate with KEPRO, our Quality Improvement Organization, who spoke on “Self-Care: Remaining Resilient.”

Last, but certainly not least, thanks to every D1-1 employee who participated. You're the best!

September 26, 2019 at 1:32 PM ·

Winners of the Floyd County Youth Photo Voice Contest have been announced. Sponsored by the Georgia Department of Public Health Northwest Health District and the Floyd County Health Department, the contest challenged Floyd County high school and college students to submit a photo with a caption or short story answering the question “What does a healthy Floyd County mean to you?”.

From dozens of submissions, these winners were selected:

1st place----Katie Sweeney, Berry College
2nd place--- Shaira Ramirez, Rome High School
3rd place--- Ian Van Riper, Georgia Tech

The photo contest was held in conjunction with a community health assessment, conducted by the Northwest Health District, of Floyd County and its residents.
###
Katelyn Louise Photography

Over 300 Georgia Department of Public Health (GA DPH) Northwest Health District employees, including staff from all ten county health departments, gathered Wednesday, September 18, on the Georgia Northwestern Technical College campus in Calhoun for Wellness Day 2019.
Keynote speakers were Jennifer Burkholder, GA DPH deputy chief nurse of emerging health threats, who spoke about “Finding Meaning in Adversity” and Maura Kalafut, an associate with KEPRO, our Quality Improvement Organization, who spoke on “Self-Care: Remaining Resilient.”

Other wellness-related group and individual table activities were interspersed throughout the day. The enthusiasm and positive energy generated whenever we all gather was infectious and carried home to our respective counties at the end of the day to help us personally, but more importantly, collectively as we work to make the citizens of Northwest Georgia safer and healthier.
text:
Over 300 Georgia Department of Public Health (GA DPH) Northwest Health District employees, including staff from all ten county health departments, gathered Wednesday, September 18, on the Georgia Northwestern Technical College campus in Calhoun for Wellness Day 2019.
Keynote speakers were Jennifer Burkholder, GA DPH deputy chief nurse of emerging health threats, who spoke about “Finding Meaning in Adversity” and Maura Kalafut, an associate with KEPRO, our Quality Improvement Organization, who spoke on “Self-Care: Remaining Resilient.”

Other wellness-related group and individual table activities were interspersed throughout the day. The enthusiasm and positive energy generated whenever we all gather was infectious and carried home to our respective counties at the end of the day to help us personally, but more importantly, collectively as we work to make the citizens of Northwest Georgia safer and healthier.

Here’s why. If you work in food service and get hepatitis A, you can unknowingly contaminate food or drink and make customers sick. You can also infect co-workers.

You’re going to feel bad for a couple of weeks or longer and might be hospitalized. In extreme cases, you could die. You could be out of work and miss paychecks. You might hurt your employer’s business and jeopardize or lose your job.

Help prevent the spread of hep A. Get vaccinated, glove up, wash hands thoroughly after using the restroom and between tasks, and follow your Employee Health Policy.

For addresses and contact information for the most convenient Northwest Georgia health department, please go to: https://nwgapublichealth.org/counties
#HepatitisA

post_text: Polk County Health Department Registered Nurse Amy Tillman Norris received the Maggie Kline Nursing Award at the recent Georgia Public Health Association Annual Meeting in Atlanta. The award honors Maggie Kline who for years coordinated the continuing education program for public health nurses in Georgia. It recognizes a public health nurse or a public health nurse specialist who exceptionally fulfills the nursing role in service delivery to public health clients and families. Norris is the daughter of Lynn Tillman, longtime operations support coordinator at the health department. Presenting the award to Norris (center) are GPHA President Dr. Colin Smith (l) and Polk County Health Department Nurse Manager Malindy Ely (r).

post_text:
The CDC reported yesterday a 300 percent increase in hepatitis A cases in recent years, blaming most on person-to-person transmission among drug abusers and the homeless. This brief news story explains in simple terms why this is happening, who's most at risk, and how to prevent contracting hep A.

Health departments in Bartow, Catoosa, Chattooga, Dade, Floyd, Gordon, and Walker Counties will provide free hepatitis A vaccine to individuals at risk of the highly contagious, highly preventable liver disease every Friday in May. Clinics will be held at each health department on May 17, 24, and 31, from 8 am to 2 pm.
For more information, contact your local county health department.

https://www.upi.com/Health_News/2019/05/10/CDC-Hepatitis-A-infections-up-300-percent-in-last-three-years/5351557493140/

Today, Monday, May 6, is National Nurses Day. We thank all nurses for doing what they do, but we'd especially like to thank a very special category of nurses - public health nurses - for using their skills to lead changes that improve health for individuals, populations, and communities. These include the nurses that provide healthcare and community leadership at your local county health department.
#NationalNursesDay
